##International Public Health experts: The key is not in the inflection point, to see what criteria to determine the eradication of the epidemic

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

The following article is from the Chinese Philanthropist magazine, by Gao Xiaowen

China News Service, director, China Newsweek. Based in China, we focus on global charity and social issues, providing professional and rational reports and analyses with depth and temperature.

Public Health epidemiologists should be allowed to speak

Allow doctors to discuss;

Be Transparent and don't be afraid of social chaos

A little chaos avoids a lot of chaos

February 7 evening, medical staff ready to enter the living room of Wuhan "Shelter Hospital" for work.

As of 2400 hours on February 14,66,492 confirmed cases (54,406 in Hubei and 37,914 in Wuhan) and 1,523 deaths (1,457 in Hubei and 1,123 in Wuhan) have been reported, according to the National Health Commission. Although the number of newly confirmed cases in other provinces is declining, the epidemic prevention and control work in Wuhan and Hubei is still in a stalemate and tight phase.

In view of the latest development of the epidemic situation of new coronavirus at home and abroad, and how to reflect on China's major disease prevention and control system and public health management system, etc. , on February 14, zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of the Public Health at Ucla and a senior tenured professor of epidemiology, spoke to Chinese philanthropist again.

The whole world has no experience

Chinese philanthropist: Please tell us about the global incidence of the new coronavirus. What are its characteristics? What effective prevention and control measures have been taken by various countries at present? Will the outbreak turn into a global pandemic?

Zhang Style: On February 11, at an international conference organized by World Health Organization on New Crown Pneumonia, Director General Tan Desai sent two messages: the first is to officially name the disease caused by COVID-19 infection "COVID-19" , and the CO stands for Corona, vI stands for Virus, D for Disease, and 19 for 2019. The name has now become a universal one. Second, Tan Desai said that npv pneumonia is now the world's public enemy number one, and the threat to the world is very serious, perhaps even greater than the impact of terrorism on the world's political, economic and social impact.

As of Feb. 14,528 cases of new coronavirus pneumonia had been reported in 25 countries outside China, including two deaths, one in the Philippines and one in Japan, according to World Health Organization. Countries with the highest number of cases included Japan with 255, Singapore with 67, Thailand with 33, South Korea with 28, Malaysia with 19, Australia with 16 and Vietnam with 16. The characteristics of cases abroad: First, most of the patients had contact history in Wuhan, Hubei or other parts of China, second, there were relatively few severe cases, third, the death rate was 0.38% .

A medical officer looks at a CT scan of a patient's lung on Feb. 3.

Prevention and control measures vary from country to country. In the United States, for example, when a new case of pneumonia is diagnosed, patients are classified: Those with mild cases are placed in isolation at home, and those with severe cases are placed in isolation wards in isolation hospitals. Patients with mild illness, as soon as the situation, the hospital to call admission treatment. The first American plane to evacuate Chinese nationals from Wuhan landed in Los Angeles. The passengers on board had been quarantined for 14 days at an air force base. None of the patients showed up, and they all went home on February 12.

There have been 15 patients in the United States so far, including one who was mislabeled during the first kit test and later found to be positive, and who has since left, and then called him back in for quarantine. Sample tests, including those from the U.S. CDC, can lead to missed diagnoses if there is no rigorous quality control, or if there is a slight oversight in the process. So this is not a unique problem for China, but for the United States and the rest of the world. Because this is a new epidemic, nobody has any experience with it. It is difficult to say whether the epidemic will translate into a global pandemic, as the importance of the disease varies from country to country.

So far, superspreaders have also been found overseas. Stevie Walsh, a 53 year old British man, was at a meeting in Singapore from January 20 to 22 when he came into contact with an infected person from Hubei Province who was traveling from Singapore to France, Switzerland to the UK, inadvertently transmitted the virus to 11 people from at least three countries, who may have passed it on to others. The discovery of this super-carrier actually shows that the new coronavirus is very infectious, so we must be vigilant.

In Wuhan, there has been an outbreak of family group cases, mainly because some patients can not get into hospitals, or live with their families without adequate self-isolation, or because the space in their homes is relatively small, this can easily lead to mass outbreaks. In the United States, patient home segregation is a very strict method, including confined to their own room, do not share tableware, toilet or living room, kitchen, to prevent the spread of their disease to family members. Therefore, the family group of cases accelerated outbreak, through the patient's self-isolation or hospital isolation, the risk to the family will be reduced, can be avoided.

Now the domestic report still has some asymptomatic patients, test positive patients can be transmitted to other people, so we should be very vigilant. But I personally think that this asymptomatic case may be that the virus he carries is not too strong, so he passed on to others the symptoms may not be too serious. This is a scientific hypothesis that will have to be tested in the future.

It's not the inflection point that matters

Chinese philanthropist: There are two views on the survival conditions of the new coronavirus: those that are active in low temperatures and those that can survive in warmer weather. What do you think? Will the new coronavirus mutate?

Zhang: As for the effect of temperature on the new coronavirus, now many people in China may think that the spring bloom will not cause the disappearance of the disease. In the light of the SARS epidemic, it began in November 2002 and ended in early July 2003, covering a period of nearly eight months. Therefore, the forecast of temperature on the impact of new coronavirus, may not be accurate. Because in Singapore, Malaysia, the Philippines, Hong Kong, Guangzhou and other relatively hot places, there are morbidity. It's spring in Los Angeles, but we still have patients. So we can not relax, waiting for the arrival of spring flowers, should still be ready.

On the question of whether the virus will mutate, so far no obvious changes have been seen. But if there is a mutation, the virus's virulence may rise or fall. It's hard to tell from Wuhan or Hubei Right now, but in general it's clear from other provinces and cities whether the momentum is up or down. Specifically, it depends on whether the proportion of severe cases in other provinces and cities has declined since January 20. If there is a downward trend, it may indicate that the virus has become less virulent. But it's hard to say, because the definition of a severe case may vary from place to place. Based on the assumption that viruses co exist with humans, many virologists believe that viruses need to survive as they spread, so they become progressively less virulent to humans, perhaps like influenza. I hope it's for the best.

"Chinese philanthropist" : February 14, with the exception of Hubei, the country's other provinces newly confirmed cases to achieve a "ten consecutive decline. Does this mean that the epidemic is entering a plateau? According to the current incidence of data, whether to judge the National Epidemic Inflection Point has arrived?

Zhang Style: the first thing is to know what the definition of inflection point is. The so-called inflection point is there is a peak in the incidence, and then the epidemic continued to decline for a certain period of time. This time depends on how we decide, some people suggest 14 days is an incubation period, some people suggest 7 days is a cycle. If set at 7 days, many places may have reached the inflection point, because in the last 7 days, all provinces and cities except Hubei, the number of cases have dropped correspondingly. Conservatively speaking, it can be fixed for 14 days, so it is relatively smooth to see an inflection point. At the same time, may also be affected by the recent return tide, the vast majority of people who return to work in the city may have a disease, will increase the number of disease. In this case, continue to observe for another week, so that it can be said with great confidence that the inflection point of the epidemic has been seen.

Nationally, the incidence of new pneumonia dropped 48 percent in the week from Feb. 4 to Feb. 11. It's very impressive. But on Feb. 12, a sudden increase in new cases in Hubei Province, due to a change in diagnostic criteria, led to a surge of more than 15,000 new cases nationwide that day. Because this is not a natural increase, it changes the trend analysis of new cases nationwide. More than 60 percent of the drop was in Guangdong, Zhejiang, Henan, Shanghai, Beijing, Shandong and Anhui. If we don't see a significant increase in new cases, while the local incidence continues to decline, then the inflection point of the epidemic in all provinces and cities except Hubei is basically on February 4.

A lot of people are talking about whether the return wave will cause a rise in the incidence. Of course it's possible, because these people are coming back from all over the country, especially from the highly endemic provinces and cities. Is it possible that they could have brought back the local virus, could they be asymptomatic? It's understandable that we're all concerned. On the other hand, however, the vast majority of those returning have been in isolation for at least two weeks, if they do not become ill during isolation, plus a one-to two-week home isolation requirement for those returning, there won't be much new arrivals during this period. I'm optimistic about that.

The more important question now is not the inflection point of the epidemic, but the criteria for determining the complete eradication of new crown pneumonia. For the control of a Emerging Infectious Diseases disease, the WHO standard is that after the last patient has been treated, we can declare a complete end of the disease with no new patients for 28 days in both incubation periods. But this is a very difficult task. First, the onset should continue to drop to zero, and second, all patients should be carefully treated so that they can recover as soon as possible, all the way to the last patient, The Adventure of the Resident Patient said. And wait two more incubation periods. So now the work is very difficult, not only to find patients, but also to treat patients. After we cure all the patients, we have to wait two incubation periods.

Onlookers and guards stand guard at the West Railway Station in Beijing February 8,2010.

Chinese philanthropist: With the end of the Spring Festival holiday and the resumption of work by enterprises, the closure and isolation measures taken earlier around the country are faced with the contradiction between the resumption of work and production. In this case, the previous prevention and control measures need to continue, or can make appropriate adjustments?

Zhang: The resumption of work may have some impact on the prevention and control of the epidemic, because the returning workers are mainly concentrated in the cities with large population mobility, such as Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen. I think most of the people coming back from work have been closed and quarantined for at least two weeks. If there is no disease during this period, their risk is relatively low.

The worst fear is asymptomatic carriers. In this case, if they can not work from home, according to the situation in various places, they should observe one enterprise after another to see how their prevention and control measures are, if their prevention and control measures are more complete, we can consider them back at work. If there is a strict resumption of work prevention and control conditions, it can also avoid the epidemic of disease after resumption of work.

We should pay attention to some specific problems in resuming work. Some people who work in big cities don't have their own houses in the area, and some of these renters might not let them in if the neighborhoods are closed. I think community managers need to understand this and work through it. These people also need to keep working and need a living environment.

In addition, there are some people who have returned to work as vendors or retail workers, and I think we should give them a chance to survive, because their lives are totally dependent on these tools. There have to be measures to protect these people, as well as others. Therefore, the whole society should have a comprehensive consideration, if it is only for prevention and control, it will also affect the whole social economy.

Trauma is not to be underestimated

Chinese philanthropist: As of February 11,1,716 people had been infected by health care workers fighting the epidemic, according to the National Health Commission. Excuse me in remedial process, how does medical worker do oneself defend a job, how to guide psychological pressure and negative mood?

Zhang Style: Why would there be a large number of current medical staff infection? In my opinion, the main reason is that the preparatory work for the closure of Wuhan was inadequate. Due to the psychological panic caused by the closure of the city, a large number of patients and non-patients flooded into the hospital. Although there are many hospitals in Wuhan, but the bearing capacity is not too strong, the doctor's bearing capacity is also limited, which actually caused the collapse of the medical staff or the whole hospital.

In Emerging Infectious Diseases of an epidemic, information should be transparent so that health care workers are trained to know how to protect themselves. At the same time, hospitals should also train medical staff, not only for fever clinics, all departments should be trained. First, let the medical staff know the seriousness of the disease; second, there should be enough protective equipment to protect the medical staff. So far it seems that the preparation work is very insufficient, which is also caused by a large number of health care workers a major cause of illness.

A recent report says that 41% OF PATIENTS IN WUHAN -- As if -- were hospital acquired, more than 20% of them by health care workers. That means at least one in five patients is infected by a health care worker. In this way, the medical staff in Wuhan is infected with a very serious situation. It can be seen that the hospital infection is very serious, because some patients can not enter the hospital, he ran around in society, to the hospital infection hospital healthy people and medical staff. Pretty much every hospital in the country.

The trauma of the siege can not be underestimated. Psychological trauma of patients and quarantined, post-disaster syndrome of doctors and nurses, deep psychological trauma of the family members of the deceased, psychological shadow of children during the period of house closure in the city. These serious psychological problems, if the people in Wuhan can not receive timely and targeted psychological counseling and treatment, and can not vent through various channels, mental illness caused by psychological trauma will increase a lot, affect the healthy development of the society.

It is recommended that psychiatric specialists be involved in the selection of medical teams, that universities with psychology departments conduct internet-based psychological counselling and treatment, and that social media be allowed to give the public outlets for psychological release, encourage people in a position to do so to write about their pain. It is particularly important to provide timely psychological intervention to children, especially those whose loved ones have died of illness, so as to avoid the psychological shadow caused by the plague to accompany them throughout their lives and affect their healthy growth.

Chinese philanthropist: In view of the problems exposed during the response to the epidemic, can we talk about how China's Disease Prevention and control system and mechanism should be further improved and perfected?

Zhang: First, there are already nearly 100 public health colleges and medical schools in China, which train many undergraduate and graduate students in public health. The problem is that many of the trained talents are not put to use, this is mainly because the importance of public health is not fully recognized by the State and society. To train high-level public health epidemiologists, when the key can lead the control of the epidemic.

Second, to strengthen the teaching and research of Acute Infectious Diseases (or Emerging Infectious Diseases) in each public health college, and to establish Emerging Infectious Diseases doctoral degrees and postdoctoral work stations in key public health colleges.

Third, strengthen the international exchange of the Emerging Infectious Diseases, participate in the Emerging Infectious Diseases in each country's epidemic prevention, increase domestic experts in Emerging Infectious Diseases emergency preparedness and Response Capacity.

Fourth, strengthen the CDC from the state to the provinces and cities, public institutions into administrative units, improve treatment, retain talent.

Fifth, the CDC at all levels of acute infectious disease supporting the preparation of the team, usually scattered in all departments, under the state of emergency can be pulled out of the war.

Sixthly, when leaders of health committees and Centers for Disease Control and prevention are appointed, priority should be given to those with a background in public health epidemiology and emergency response capabilities in emergency infectious disease control. This is particularly important at the level of national and provincial health committees and CDC.

Seventh, to be transparent, do not be afraid of small social chaos, small chaos can avoid chaos. Do not apply stability thinking to the prevention and control of acute infectious diseases. Allow Public Health epidemiologists to express their opinions and allow doctors to discuss them.

Eighth, respect the privacy of patients and their families, in the course of treatment and isolation, to give humane care to patients and their families and friends.

Chinese philanthropist: How can the international community work together to combat the spread of new crown pneumonia in countries around the world?

Controlling the spread of the new coronavirus is not a challenge for China alone, Zhang said. As a global community, China's problems are also those of other countries. In the prevention and control of the new coronavirus, if there is no joint efforts of the world, China alone is not easy to do well.

First, strengthening cooperation among countries around the world and inviting experts with experience in the Emerging Infectious Diseases to participate in prevention and control in China can not only learn from their experience in prevention and control, but also promote the advantages of China's prevention and control of diseases. WHO experts have recently come to China, and other countries are interested and should actively invite them to join the exchange and learn from the experience and lessons of the Emerging Infectious Diseases in different parts of the world.

Second, co-operation on diagnostic reagents is critical, as a lack of sensitivity and specificity can lead to false positives and false negatives. So it's best to work with the rest of the world to optimize the diagnostic kit. This avoids the possibility that patients who are indeed new coronaviruses will not be diagnosed, and reduces the risk of The Adventure of the Resident Patient spreading the virus in society.

Third, Start Doing Serum Antibody Studies, which we call sero-epidemiology. In fact, resistance can be used to map out an entire community of infections. Now there are a lot of people in the community who have recovered, who have been studying their antibodies, and through the design of the antibodies, you can see how many people are actually getting sick in this epidemic. In addition, send someone to one of the better public health in the United States to train and become a Emerging Infectious Diseases specialist, and when that happens, they can come into play.
